## D-02 · Vector Store — pgvector (Neon) over Chroma / Pinecone

**Decision:** Use the pgvector extension on the existing Neon Postgres instance for
embedding storage and similarity search.

**Context:** RAG context retrieval is per-agent (each agent queries only its relevant
chunks). We already have a Postgres instance (Neon).

**Alternatives considered:**

- Chroma — self-hosted, adds Docker service; no managed free tier
- Pinecone — free tier limited to 1 index, 100k vectors; managed but separate service
- Qdrant Cloud — free tier exists; separate service adds ops overhead

**Rejected because:** Adding a separate vector DB service adds operational complexity and
cost. pgvector on Neon eliminates the service boundary — embeddings and relational data
in one place, one backup, one connection pool.

---

## D-03 · Task Queue — Upstash Redis over Celery / RabbitMQ / SQS

**Decision:** Use Upstash Redis (serverless) as the async job queue between the webhook
handler and the worker process.

**Context:** Webhook handler must return HTTP 202 within ~1s. The agent pipeline takes
30–120s. A durable queue with at-least-once delivery is required.

**Alternatives considered:**

- Celery + RabbitMQ — production-grade but heavy; RabbitMQ needs a separate server
- Python asyncio background tasks (FastAPI BackgroundTasks) — no persistence; lost on restart
- AWS SQS — reliable but not free; adds cloud vendor dependency
- PostgreSQL SKIP LOCKED queue (pg_boss pattern) — viable but adds polling complexity

**Rejected because:** RabbitMQ/Celery adds significant DevOps overhead. asyncio tasks
lose jobs on process restart. Upstash Redis has a 10k requests/day free tier, is
serverless, and fits the Render + worker process model cleanly.

