## D-12 · Auth — Signed JWT Session over Refresh Tokens / Cookie Sessions

**Decision:** Issue a signed JWT (HS256, 7-day expiry) as the session token after GitHub
OAuth callback. Store in localStorage on the frontend; send as Bearer header.

**Context:** Dashboard is internal tooling for repo owners / org admins. Simplicity
trumps enterprise-grade session management for v1.

**Alternatives considered:**

- Refresh token rotation — more secure but adds token refresh logic on both ends
- HttpOnly cookie sessions — avoids localStorage XSS risk but complicates CORS for SPA
- Supabase Auth — removes custom JWT logic but adds a hard dependency
- GitHub OAuth token as session — leaks GitHub scope; can't encode app-specific claims

**Rejected because:** Refresh token rotation adds frontend complexity. HttpOnly cookies
require careful SameSite/CORS configuration for Vercel → Render cross-origin calls.
Supabase Auth is overkill. 7-day JWT is acceptable for an internal dashboard; rotate by
forcing re-login on expiry.

**Security note:** JWT secret must be ≥256-bit random value stored in environment
variable. Never hardcode. Rotate by changing the env var (all existing sessions invalidate).

